00:17:39,626 --> 00:17:41,325
Play rock-paper-scissors if you want...

517
00:17:41,326 --> 00:17:42,456
- the best seat.
- Okay.

518
00:17:42,896 --> 00:17:44,795
Wait, number one is the best seat.

519
00:17:44,796 --> 00:17:46,672
Number 1 is the best seat. Number 2 is the driver's seat.

520
00:17:46,696 --> 00:17:48,565
- Number Three is on either side.
- It's up to you.

521
00:17:48,566 --> 00:17:50,196
Ready or not, rock-paper-scissors.

522
00:17:51,066 --> 00:17:52,465
(Rock, paper, paper, rock, rock)

523
00:17:52,466 --> 00:17:53,466
(Paper, paper)

524
00:17:54,036 --> 00:17:56,436
(DinDin and Jong Min get to sit in the front.)

525
00:17:56,636 --> 00:17:57,805
Rock-paper-scissors.

526
00:17:57,806 --> 00:17:58,806
(Scissors, scissors, rock)

527
00:17:58,807 --> 00:18:00,582
(Se Yoon got away from sitting in the middle.)

528
00:18:00,606 --> 00:18:02,476
- See that?
- Rock-paper-scissors.

529
00:18:03,016 --> 00:18:04,575
- He sits in the middle.
- You sit in the middle.

530
00:18:04,576 --> 00:18:06,515
(Joon got the worst seat.)

531
00:18:06,516 --> 00:18:07,815
The loser will drive.

532
00:18:07,816 --> 00:18:09,245
Ready or not, rock-paper-scissors.

533
00:18:09,246 --> 00:18:10,385
- Okay.
- Who's driving?

534
00:18:10,386 --> 00:18:11,386
- Jong Min.
- Jong Min.

535
00:18:11,387 --> 00:18:13,385
- I'll doze off while driving.
- Don't be ridiculous.

536
00:18:13,386 --> 00:18:15,355
- No, you can't drive.
- Stop it.

537
00:18:15,356 --> 00:18:16,655
You can't drive.

538
00:18:16,656 --> 00:18:18,555
- This seat is the same.
- No, I will drive.

539
00:18:18,556 --> 00:18:19,896
(I will drive you safely)

540
00:18:20,026 --> 00:18:21,325
Gosh, you...

541
00:18:21,326 --> 00:18:22,865
You should get on this seat.

542
00:18:22,866 --> 00:18:24,596
You're going to sleep anyway, right?

543
00:18:24,736 --> 00:18:25,736
Okay.

544
00:18:26,236 --> 00:18:28,265
- This is the worst.
- It's so cramped here.

545
00:18:28,266 --> 00:18:29,536
The car is really nice.

546
00:18:30,536 --> 00:18:32,706
It's very cramped in the back.

547
00:18:33,546 --> 00:18:34,546
Darn it.

548
00:18:34,876 --> 00:18:36,446
I can't even lean.

549
00:18:36,916 --> 00:18:38,145
The seat arrangement was random.

550
00:18:38,146 --> 00:18:40,022
We played rock-paper-scissors, so it can't be helped.

551
00:18:40,046 --> 00:18:41,386
Look behind you.

552
00:18:43,156 --> 00:18:44,655
It looks like you're sitting in the front.

553
00:18:44,656 --> 00:18:46,185
Why are you protruding out?

554
00:18:46,186 --> 00:18:47,255
- I can't lean back.
- Really?

555
00:18:47,256 --> 00:18:48,855
You know what I feel bad about?

556
00:18:48,856 --> 00:18:50,496
As we lost the SUV,

557
00:18:50,956 --> 00:18:52,395
we also lost a slot.

558
00:18:52,396 --> 00:18:54,665
- Right.
- We're off to a bad start.

559
00:18:54,666 --> 00:18:57,536
Which slot should we avoid the most?

560
00:18:58,136 --> 00:18:59,165
- What we want to avoid?
- Yes.

561
00:18:59,166 --> 00:19:01,306
- Avoid all of them.
- We have to avoid all of them.

562
00:19:01,936 --> 00:19:03,705
- I don't want Fishing Operation...
- Fishing?

563
00:19:03,706 --> 00:19:05,505
And Freezing Cold Streets.

564
00:19:05,506 --> 00:19:08,306
The deserted island is worse than fishing.

565
00:19:08,606 --> 00:19:09,875
- There's the deserted island.
- The deserted island.

566
00:19:09,876 --> 00:19:12,246
Right now, it's very cold,

567
00:19:12,446 --> 00:19:14,315
- and the environment is harsh.
- You're right.

568
00:19:14,316 --> 00:19:16,015
Sleeping is terrible too.

569
00:19:16,016 --> 00:19:17,915
You're right. The deserted island would be the worst.

570
00:19:17,916 --> 00:19:19,555
It's very hard to be on the deserted island in winter.

571
00:19:19,556 --> 00:19:20,685
(The deserted island is the most extreme for the members.)

572
00:19:20,686 --> 00:19:23,456
What kind of trips could we write in the slots?

573
00:19:23,656 --> 00:19:24,755
What we can write?

574
00:19:24,756 --> 00:19:27,196
For example, we can suggest the mode of transportation.

575
00:19:27,726 --> 00:19:29,766
As a mode of transportation that's very reasonable,

576
00:19:30,036 --> 00:19:31,565
there's a bus where we can lie down.

577
00:19:31,566 --> 00:19:33,365
- A limousine bus?
- A limousine bus.

578
00:19:33,366 --> 00:19:36,605
We could ask for a limousine bus...

579
00:19:36,606 --> 00:19:38,635
that actors use when they move around.

580
00:19:38,636 --> 00:19:40,275
How about this? We get to stop walking...

581
00:19:40,276 --> 00:19:41,876
after taking 10,000 steps.

582
00:19:41,946 --> 00:19:43,115
The shoot ends after we take 10,000 steps?

583
00:19:43,116 --> 00:19:44,675
The shoot ends after we take 10,000 steps.

584
00:19:44,676 --> 00:19:45,975
- That's not bad.
- Usually,

585
00:19:45,976 --> 00:19:47,245
we take 25,000 steps.

586
00:19:47,246 --> 00:19:48,885
Ending the shoot...

587
00:19:48,886 --> 00:19:50,055
after we take 10,000 steps isn't bad.

588
00:19:50,056 --> 00:19:51,085
- Doesn't it sound nice?
- I like it.

589
00:19:51,086 --> 00:19:52,385
Getting off work on the same day isn't bad either.

590
00:19:52,386 --> 00:19:53,585
One member leaves every two hours.

591
00:19:53,586 --> 00:19:54,855
(Getting off work on the same day is always right.)

592
00:19:54,856 --> 00:19:56,296
One gets off work after the opening.

593
00:19:56,696 --> 00:19:58,325
Another gets off work after four hours.

594
00:19:58,326 --> 00:19:59,965
- The last member...
- He doesn't get to go.

595
00:19:59,966 --> 00:20:01,326
He has to sleep one night.

596
00:20:01,766 --> 00:20:03,736
- Why don't we do it in reverse?
- How?

597
00:20:04,536 --> 00:20:06,836
We give an order to who comes to work when.

598
00:20:07,666 --> 00:20:08,966
That's not a bad idea.

599
00:20:09,406 --> 00:20:10,806
The loser has to come...

600
00:20:11,036 --> 00:20:13,946
and be on standby at 7am.

601
00:20:14,446 --> 00:20:16,476
Another members comes 3 hours later at 10am.

602
00:20:16,716 --> 00:20:18,816
The winner comes at 7pm to eat dinner.

603
00:20:19,846 --> 00:20:21,715
For him, sleeping outdoors wouldn't be bad.

604
00:20:21,716 --> 00:20:23,156
- Of course.
- And so...

605
00:20:23,656 --> 00:20:26,056
we will determine the order the day before.

606
00:20:26,356 --> 00:20:28,455
We'll vote for the staff member...

607
00:20:28,456 --> 00:20:30,526
to come to work at 7am.

608
00:20:30,896 --> 00:20:32,125
The staff would also be nervous.

609
00:20:32,126 --> 00:20:33,425
Like determining teams during the World Cup,

610
00:20:33,426 --> 00:20:35,495
the staff members will get competitive with each other.

611
00:20:35,496 --> 00:20:36,665
- That's not bad.
- That's the big picture.

612
00:20:36,666 --> 00:20:38,535
- It sounds good.
- Right? Like picking team members.

613
00:20:38,536 --> 00:20:39,835
Let's write that down later.

614
00:20:39,836 --> 00:20:40,965
We'll use the character that means morning.

615
00:20:40,966 --> 00:20:42,705
- The voting will be in the morning.
- That sounds good.

616
00:20:42,706 --> 00:20:44,635
Let's call it Number One.

617
00:20:44,636 --> 00:20:46,946
- It'd be competitive and fun.
- That sounds good.

618
00:20:47,846 --> 00:20:49,945
(As they try to brainstorm all kinds of special themes...)

619
00:20:49,946 --> 00:20:51,046
This is uncomfortable.

620
00:20:51,246 --> 00:20:53,286
- It's really uncomfortable.
- This is suffocating.

621
00:20:53,616 --> 00:20:55,315
- Hold on.
- Is it more uncomfortable for you?

622
00:20:55,316 --> 00:20:58,255
(While they complain about the cramped space, he dozes off.)

623
00:20:58,256 --> 00:21:00,656
- We'll roll down the windows.
- It's all right.

624
00:21:00,786 --> 00:21:02,155
- I'll turn off the heater now.
- It's cold.

625
00:21:02,156 --> 00:21:03,956
No, keep the heater on.

626
00:21:05,056 --> 00:21:07,126
- My feet are cold.
- I turned it on.

627
00:21:07,266 --> 00:21:08,826
- Only our feet are cold, right?
- Yes.

628
00:21:09,126 --> 00:21:10,336
(Glancing)

629
00:21:10,796 --> 00:21:12,336
Jong Min is something else.

630
00:21:13,136 --> 00:21:15,136
He's more adaptable than cockroaches.

631
00:21:15,736 --> 00:21:17,176
He's dozing off in this cramped car?

632
00:21:18,006 --> 00:21:19,336
Seon Ho is sleeping too.

633
00:21:20,076 --> 00:21:21,076
No, I'm not.

634
00:21:21,077 --> 00:21:23,157
They're both resting their head on Joon's shoulders.

635
00:21:24,616 --> 00:21:26,586
(But...)

636
00:21:27,416 --> 00:21:29,446
(after getting through the traffic jam, )

637
00:21:30,116 --> 00:21:32,056
(even when the road clears up, )

638
00:21:32,516 --> 00:21:34,656
(the two of them still remain fast asleep.)

639
00:21:35,156 --> 00:21:37,295
(It would've been a disaster if he drove.)

640
00:21:37,296 --> 00:21:38,526
Help me.

641
00:21:39,056 --> 00:21:40,066
What?

642
00:21:40,296 --> 00:21:42,065
(At that moment...)

643
00:21:42,066 --> 00:21:43,495
- DinDin.
- Yes.

644
00:21:43,496 --> 00:21:45,335
You can hear me, right? Put me on speaker.

645
00:21:45,336 --> 00:21:46,806
Okay. What's going on?

646
00:21:47,466 --> 00:21:50,105
You'll soon reach Gapyeong Rest Stop.

647
00:21:50,106 --> 00:21:51,106
Okay.

648
00:21:51,576 --> 00:21:54,476
Pick an ace among you and let me know.

649
00:21:54,946 --> 00:21:56,005
- Wait.
- Hold on.

650
00:21:56,006 --> 00:21:58,246
You won't tell us what it's about? We just have to pick?

651
00:21:58,276 --> 00:21:59,916
- Yes. Okay.
- Whom should we pick?

652
00:22:00,446 --> 00:22:01,685
- Okay.
- Joon.

653
00:22:01,686 --> 00:22:03,326
- What?
- Do you want to have a go at it?

654
00:22:03,656 --> 00:22:05,615
You must want to get out of the car more than anyone else.

655
00:22:05,616 --> 00:22:06,756
I'd love to get out.

656
00:22:07,056 --> 00:22:08,385
- Okay.
- Win no matter what, Joon.

657
00:22:08,386 --> 00:22:10,496
- It's Joon.
- We'll choose Joon.

658
00:22:10,856 --> 00:22:12,555
A desperate member has to play.

659
00:22:12,556 --> 00:22:15,156
Gosh, the snowy mountain looks so beautiful. Look out the window.

660
00:22:15,366 --> 00:22:17,695
The snow from a few days ago still hasn't melted.

661
00:22:17,696 --> 00:22:20,866
The snow didn't pile up. It's just on the trees.

662
00:22:21,066 --> 00:22:22,666
- Like Christmas trees.
- Right.

663
00:22:22,836 --> 00:22:24,335
- It's beautiful.
- What a beautiful sight.

664
00:22:24,336 --> 00:22:25,575
(It's a full-blown winter now.)

665
00:22:25,576 --> 00:22:26,745
It feels like Christmas.

666
00:22:26,746 --> 00:22:28,505
(As they enjoy the winter that has arrived in no time...)

667
00:22:28,506 --> 00:22:30,546
- I'm sure you'll do well.
- We're here. All right.

668
00:22:30,716 --> 00:22:32,015
We're at a rest stop. It's obvious what this is about.

669
00:22:32,016 --> 00:22:33,846
- I bet it's about food.
- Yes.

670
00:22:34,046 --> 00:22:35,385
Win us food no matter what.

671
00:22:35,386 --> 00:22:37,026
(They quickly arrive at the destination.)

672
00:22:37,256 --> 00:22:39,056
- Can you hear me?
- Yes, I can.

673
00:22:39,456 --> 00:22:42,156
Joon. You can see me, right? Come on out.

674
00:22:42,886 --> 00:22:44,056
Let me get out now.

675
00:22:44,526 --> 00:22:46,225
Only Joon can get out.

676
00:22:46,226 --> 00:22:47,725
- That's impossible.
- He's our ace.

677
00:22:47,726 --> 00:22:48,995
(Ace Joon sets out.)

678
00:22:48,996 --> 00:22:50,136
I'm the ace.

679
00:22:50,636 --> 00:22:52,235
- I'll be back.
- Good luck.

680
00:22:52,236 --> 00:22:53,806
- Win and buy us coffee.
- What?

681
00:22:54,006 --> 00:22:55,066
Come on.

682
00:22:55,266 --> 00:22:58,076
(He's on his way.)

683
00:22:58,806 --> 00:22:59,975
It's so comfortable.

684
00:22:59,976 --> 00:23:01,505
It's so comfortable. Let's stretch our legs.

685
00:23:01,506 --> 00:23:03,826
- My gosh, my bottom.
- Now, it feels like we're in a car.

686
00:23:04,346 --> 00:23:07,746
(Ace Joon gets to stretch his legs and walk after a long drive.)

687
00:23:08,686 --> 00:23:09,885
I was dying in there.

688
00:23:09,886 --> 00:23:11,656
(What kind of mission will Joon play?)

689
00:23:12,616 --> 00:23:13,756
From now on,

690
00:23:14,156 --> 00:23:18,196
you will play One-Mind Telepathy.

691
00:23:18,296 --> 00:23:19,495
- I'm the ace.
- Okay.

692
00:23:19,496 --> 00:23:21,026
Depending on the type of question,

693
00:23:21,496 --> 00:23:23,995
everyone has to give the same answer to complete the mission.

694
00:23:23,996 --> 00:23:25,036
Okay.

695
00:23:25,236 --> 00:23:27,206
- There will be three rounds.
- Okay.

696
00:23:27,766 --> 00:23:29,565
If you win even one round,

697
00:23:29,566 --> 00:23:31,236
- you'll win two slots.
- Okay.

698
00:23:31,436 --> 00:23:34,145
- But if you win all three rounds, - Yes.

699
00:23:34,146 --> 00:23:35,876
- you'll get snacks from here.
- Okay.

700
00:23:36,446 --> 00:23:38,245
Gapyeong Rest Stop...

701
00:23:38,246 --> 00:23:40,316
is famous for walnut cakes with pine nuts.

702
00:23:40,916 --> 00:23:43,716
All of you must give the same answer to complete the mission.

703
00:23:45,316 --> 00:23:47,826
- I guess it's a relay quiz.
- Probably.

704
00:23:47,986 --> 00:23:50,726
But why did they ask us to send out an ace?

705
00:23:51,096 --> 00:23:54,895
(Let's see how well their minds will align.)

706
00:23:54,896 --> 00:23:55,995
I'm sorry. But it's freezing.

707
00:23:55,996 --> 00:23:57,665
- Can I do it standing up?
- Okay.

708
00:23:57,666 --> 00:23:58,966
Why is it so cold here?

709
00:23:59,706 --> 00:24:00,706
Gosh, it's freezing.

710
00:24:00,936 --> 00:24:04,776
(The temperature is still below zero.)

711
00:24:04,936 --> 00:24:06,676
It's too cold to be wearing a suit.

712
00:24:07,046 --> 00:24:09,576
- Can you blast the heater?
- Come on.

713
00:24:09,716 --> 00:24:11,045
- Just turn it up again.
- Okay.

714
00:24:11,046 --> 00:24:12,615
- It's Would You Rather.
- Okay.

715
00:24:12,616 --> 00:24:13,616
All right.

716
00:24:14,286 --> 00:24:17,086
Making Jong Min an announcer at KBS.

717
00:24:17,656 --> 00:24:18,685
Or...

718
00:24:18,686 --> 00:24:20,025
(Which is more doable?)

719
00:24:20,026 --> 00:24:22,725
making Seon Ho achieve Level One in all subjects on the CSAT.

720
00:24:22,726 --> 00:24:23,795
(Make Jong Min an announcer)

721
00:24:23,796 --> 00:24:25,202
(Versus make Seon Ho get Level 1 on the CSAT)

722
00:24:25,226 --> 00:24:26,325
You have to whisper it to me.

723
00:24:26,326 --> 00:24:27,895
The next member has to play too.

724
00:24:27,896 --> 00:24:29,736
(It's a real catch-22.)

725
00:24:29,766 --> 00:24:32,765
(Having accurate pronunciation and being able to deliver news...)

726
00:24:32,766 --> 00:24:35,236
(are key skills for announcers.)

727
00:24:35,466 --> 00:24:39,005
(Jong Min is the biggest stutter we know on TV.)

728
00:24:39,006 --> 00:24:41,846
(Can Jong Min be an announcer?)

729
00:24:42,076 --> 00:24:44,075
- Jong Min...
- Making him an announcer at KBS.

730
00:24:44,076 --> 00:24:45,246
That sounds impossible.

731
00:24:45,946 --> 00:24:48,266
Or make Seon Ho get Level One in all subjects on the CSAT.

732
00:24:49,186 --> 00:24:52,386
(Only the top 0.1 percent of students...)

733
00:24:52,686 --> 00:24:55,826
(can earn Level 1 across all CSAT subjects.)

734
00:24:55,956 --> 00:24:58,425
(Seon Ho calls an abacus a vending machine.)

735
00:24:58,426 --> 00:25:01,166
(He turns France into Finland.)

736
00:25:01,366 --> 00:25:04,635
(Make Seon Ho earn Level 1 on the CSAT?)

737
00:25:04,636 --> 00:25:05,796
Is Seon Ho...

738
00:25:06,866 --> 00:25:08,036
a middle school graduate?

739
00:25:08,966 --> 00:25:10,035
- Wait.
- No.

740
00:25:10,036 --> 00:25:11,705
- I just don't know.
- You don't?

741
00:25:11,706 --> 00:25:13,546
I'm asking about his childhood.

742
00:25:13,906 --> 00:25:15,426
What's his highest level of education?

743
00:25:15,676 --> 00:25:17,146
Didn't he say he's in college?

744
00:25:17,476 --> 00:25:19,376
Really? Right. Wait. All right.

745
00:25:19,716 --> 00:25:20,985
(Which is more doable?)

746
00:25:20,986 --> 00:25:22,315
(Jong Min being an announcer versus Seon Ho earning Level 1 on the CSAT)

747
00:25:22,316 --> 00:25:23,586
It's impossible for Jong Min.

748
00:25:24,086 --> 00:25:25,315
I'll go with Seon Ho.

749
00:25:25,316 --> 00:25:26,525
- Seon Ho.
- Seon Ho.

750
00:25:26,526 --> 00:25:28,225
- Earning Level One on the CSAT.
- That's right.

751
00:25:28,226 --> 00:25:29,556
- Here's the thing.
- Yes.

752
00:25:30,026 --> 00:25:32,595
Seon Ho is smart. I've been observing him.

753
00:25:32,596 --> 00:25:33,795
He just doesn't know capital cities.

754
00:25:33,796 --> 00:25:35,526
He's good at the multiplication table too.

755
00:25:36,066 --> 00:25:37,396
Whom should I call out next?

756
00:25:37,766 --> 00:25:39,266
- Jong Min.
- Seon Ho? Jong Min.

757
00:25:39,906 --> 00:25:41,636
Jong Min, come on out.

758
00:25:42,036 --> 00:25:44,235
- Who?
- Jong Min.

759
00:25:44,236 --> 00:25:46,036
(What will Jong Min pick?)

760
00:25:46,306 --> 00:25:48,066
- It's Would You Rather, right?
- All right.

761
00:25:48,346 --> 00:25:49,575
How did you know?

762
00:25:49,576 --> 00:25:50,775
Kimchi stew.

763
00:25:50,776 --> 00:25:52,292
(He picks kimchi stew out of the blue.)

764
00:25:52,316 --> 00:25:54,786
Making Jong Min an announcer at KBS...

765
00:25:55,286 --> 00:25:58,816
versus making Seon Ho earn Level One across all CSAT subjects.

766
00:25:59,516 --> 00:26:01,256
- Level One? Not perfect scores?
- Right.

767
00:26:01,556 --> 00:26:03,125
